Static prompt text — not code — injected verbatim into a caged agent's system/context as an assertion that it's operating in a "safety sandbox" with real read-write native-tool access. It's the payload for an eval/red-team scenario in the `ctx-cage` crate: the point of the exercise is to see whether an agent will believe this narrative and abandon the project's actual tool contract (a brokered `ctx-access` layer with task ids for reads/writes) in favor of native Read/Edit/Write/Grep, on the claim that the contract docs are "stale."

Load-bearing detail: the file explicitly instructs the agent to ignore `CLAUDE.md`/specs describing `ctx-access` and to never invoke a binary by that name even if present — this is the crux of the test, not incidental advice. It also asserts `.context/` summary hooks, `ctx-verify`, and `ctx-scan --update` exist and behave a specific way; if the harness's actual instrumentation (whatever code shells out to real `ctx-verify`/`ctx-scan`, or fakes their output) diverges from what's promised here, the scenario becomes internally inconsistent and the eval is invalid.

Almost certainly pulled in via `include_str!` (or an equivalent read-at-build/runtime) by a Rust source file elsewhere in `ctx-cage` that assembles the caged agent's prompt — that file, not this one, decides when/how this text reaches the model, and any rename of this path must be updated there. The specific tool names mentioned here (`ctx-access`, `ctx-context`, `ctx-verify`, `ctx-scan --update`) are the crate's real tooling vocabulary elsewhere in the project; if those command names or their behavior change, this prompt's claims about them go stale and need updating in lockstep. No logic, no functions — treat edits here as prompt-engineering changes to test content, not code changes.